The gic warning message is caused by this block of sun8i-a83t-bananapi-m3.dts.

	axp81x: pmic@3a3 {
		compatible = "x-powers,axp813";
		reg = <0x3a3>;
		interrupt-parent = <&r_intc>;
		interrupts = <GIC_SPI 32 IRQ_TYPE_LEVEL_LOW>;
		eldoin-supply = <&reg_dcdc1>;
		fldoin-supply = <&reg_dcdc5>;
		swin-supply = <&reg_dcdc1>;
		x-powers,drive-vbus-en;
	};

The interrupts line is the problem.  I gather from looking at code that low level triggered SPI interrupts are not supported.  I tried changing the gic driver to match the gicv3 driver and return EINVAL but that caused either a null pointer dereference in aw_r_intc_gicp_map_intr or a lock-related panic trying to setup DMA in aw_mmc_setup_dma.

I have not checked what Linux does with this interrupt configuration.

As for the thermal code, I think the temperature readings are garbage.

With the stock driver I get

# sysctl dev.aw_thermal
dev.aw_thermal.0.gpu: 302664C
dev.aw_thermal.0.cluster1: 302663C
dev.aw_thermal.0.cluster0: 302664C

I don't think my 2 amp power supply can get the chip that hot.  I must be seeing overflow in a83t_to_temp as the value is close to INT_MAX / A83T_TEMP_DIV.  The sensor reading should be truncated to 12 bits and treated as signed.  If I do that I see the reported temperature wander around in the range -96C to +191C.  The higher value is the maximum possible temperature that can be reported by the hardware if the register reads back all zeroes.

I am working around this for now by disabling the over temperature interrupt.
